{
  "answer": "**The Viṣṇu Smṛti enumerates the proper times for ritual bathing (alongside fire oblations) as occurring at the two twilights (morning and evening) for a Vedic student (*brahmacārin*), as part of his obligatory daily worship (*sandhyā*).*[^1]*\n\n**Full context:**  \n// Vi_28.2 // Worship at the two twilights.[^2]  \n// Vi_28.3 // He shall mutter his prayers standing at the morning twilight, and seated at the evening twilight.[^3]  \n// Vi_28.4 // The performance of bathing and the fire-oblation at both times.[^4]  \n// Vi_28.5 // Submersion in water like a staff.[^5]\n\nNo other passage in the Viṣṇu Smṛti explicitly enumerates \"proper times\" for ritual bathing in this way (e.g., no list of dawn/noon/dusk for householders). Bathing is prescribed at the \"three junctures of the day\" (*triḥsandaḥ*, i.e., morning, noon, evening) only in specific penance contexts.[^6]\n\n[^1]: Viṣṇu Smṛti, Chapter 28, [translation/](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/28/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Viṣṇu Smṛti, Chapter 28, [paragraph p-617b26](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/28/translation/#p-617b26).\n\n[^3]: Viṣṇu Smṛti, Chapter 28, [paragraph p-48ae1a](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/28/translation/#p-48ae1a).\n\n[^4]: Viṣṇu Smṛti, Chapter 28, [paragraph p-f0ea61](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/28/translation/#p-f0ea61).\n\n[^5]: Viṣṇu Smṛti, Chapter 28, [paragraph p-bece8e](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/28/translation/#p-bece8e).\n\n[^6]: E.g., Viṣṇu Smṛti 28.50, [paragraph p-c4d33e](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/28/translation/#p-c4d33e).",
